texts.html: Ask Dr. Sher A Question

I believe it is inadvisable to launch an IVF cycle of gonadotropin stimulation coming directly off of the birth control pill (BCP). Here is why: The conversion of pre-antral follicles (which do not have their FSH receptors developed) to antral follicles (which have fully responsive FSH receptors) begins about 5-7 days prior to menses. The BCP suppresses the physiological rise in the body’s own (endogenous) FSH that, in natural ovulatory cycles, takes place starting 5-7 days prior to menses. As a result,  if you initiate ovarian FSH stimulation coming directly off the BCP, it will often take 5 days or longer of stimulation with gonadotropins to first elicit conversion from pre-antral to antral follicle before significant growth in follicles and increase in blood estrogen levels will begin.

texts.html: Since endogenous release of FSH is suppressed by the BCP, it will likely take several additional days of stimulation to achieve optimal follicular development to get them ready for the hCG trigger. This can occur regardless of whether an Agonist (Lupron) “flare” protocol (where the Lupron is started with the onset of menses), whether a conventional antagonist (Cetrotide or Ganirelix) protocol is used (where the antagonist is initiated 6-8 days after the onset of menstruation or whether you gonadotropin medication is used without the addition of an agonist or an antagonist. Failure to appreciate this has led to the erroneous belief that use of the BCP (with or without Lupron) suppresses response to stimulation with FSH-containing gonadotropins. To prevent this from happening, Lupron should be administered, starting on CD21 of a natural cycle or should be overlapped with a BCP starting 5-7 days prior to menses. This will elicit a timely rise in endogenous FSH, allowing pre-antral to antral follicle conversion with optimal FSH receptor readiness for exogenous FSH exposure.

texts.html: Thus…I start my patients on a BCP (e.g. Desogen, Orthonovum 35, Lo-Estrin) within 3-4 days of the onset of menses and continue the BCP for a minimum of 10 days (usually longer). I then overlap the BCP with 10U Lupron for three days, whereupon I stop the BCP and continue daily administrations until menses. Upon menstruation, I order a blood estradiol measurement and do a pelvic ultrasound.  If the patient is ready, I either lower Lupron to 5u daily or switch from the Lupron to Ganirelix or Cetrotide at a dosage of 125mcg daily (i.e. the agonist/antagonist conversion protocol [A/ACP]). LH suppression is thereby sustained in this manner through to the hCG trigger which comprises 10,000U Pregnyl/Profasi/Novarel (or 500mcg Ovidrel). I do not use a “Lupron trigger” because the magnitude of the ensuing LH surge is unpredictable and, particularly in overstimulated patients who have a large number of follicles (i.e. the very cases where this approach is being advocated), the amount of endogenous LH may be insufficient to carry all eggs through an optimal maturational division (meiosis), resulting in far too many “immature” eggs.

texts.html: I routinely use a variation of the long pituitary down-regulation approach (whether using Lupron throughout or with the A/ACP) coming off the BCP. Women with diminished ovarian reserve (DOR) who often yield poorer eggs, more premature luteinization, and empty follicles are most suited to the A/ACP. Finally, in cases of severely diminished ovarian reserve (AMH <0.2), I add “estrogen priming” to the A/ACP approach.

texts.html: Another reason that I advise against using agonist (Lupron) “flare protocols” is that Lupron causes an immediate surge in endogenous LH release starting a few hours after Lupron is given. This causes excessive ovarian male hormone (mainly testosterone) production which can be harmful to egg development, especially when it comes to women over 40 and those who have DOR.  Clomiphene and Femara both cause increases in endogenous LH-induced ovarian testosterone, and thus I do not believe in their usage for IVF (particularly when it comes to older women or those with DOR).

texts.html: Selection of the ideal protocol for ovarian stimulation in IVF is one of the most critical treatment decisions, and can have a profound effect on egg/embryo quality and outcome.

I am pcos and have 6 failed cycles, three which I had developed OHSS using the antagonist and agonist protocols. My two sucessful cycles although miscarriages were with the antogist protocol after bcp and burseline until trigger.
I am seeing a new Dr and he suggested the antagonist protocol with Cetrotide. I have been on bcp for two months now and I’m worried this protocol will not work. I will be seeing him next week to discuss this.
What I would like to ask is if I overlapp the bcp with burseline for the last two days until my period and stopped the burseline, then on stimulation day 5/6 I introduce the cetrotide, will that create a adverse outcome or should I forget the cetrotide and continue with the burseline until trigger. My doctor says the decision is mine so just looking for advice.

texts.html: My approach is consistently to use a long pituitary DR protocol with an agonist, coming off 1-2 months on the BCP. The latter is intended to lower LH and thereby reduce stromal activation (hyperthecosis) in the hope of controlling ovarian androgen release. I then stimulate with low dosage FSHr to which I add a smidgeon of LH/hCG (Luveris/Menopur) from the 3rd day and watch for the # of follicles and [E2] starting on the 7th day of COS. If there are > 25 follicles, I keep stimulating (regardless of the [E2] until 50% of all follicles reach 14mm. Then, provided the [E2] is >2500pg/ml, I stop the agonist and the gonadotropin stimulation and follow the E2 (only) daily, without doing further US examinations. The [E2] will almost invariably climb and I watch it go up (regardless of how high the concentration of E2reaches) and track it coming down again. As soon as the [E2] drops below 2500pg/ml (and not before then ever), I administer 10,000U hCGu or hCGf (Ovidrel/Ovitrel-500mcg) as the “trigger” and perform an egg retrieval 36h later. ICSI is a MUST because “coasted” eggs usually have no cumulus oophoris and eggs without a cumulus will not readily fertilize on their own. All fertilized eggs are cultured to blastocyst (up to 6 days). And up to two (2) are transferred transvaginally under US guidance.

texts.html: The success of this approach depends on precise timing of the initiation and conclusion of “prolonged coasting”. If you start too early, follicle growth will stop and the cycle will be lost. If you start too late, you will encounter too many post-mature/cystic follicles (>22mm) that usually harbor abnormally developed eggs.

texts.html: Use of the above approach avoids unnecessary cycle cancellation, severe OHSS, and optimizes egg/embryo quality. The worst you will encounter is mild to moderate OHSS and this too is uncommon.
